        {
            "title": "Mideast War Tempers Malaysia Central Bank's Outlook for Economy in 2026",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  By Ying Xian Wong </p><br/><p>\n  KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia--Malaysia's central bank is cautiously optimistic that the economy will remain resilient this year, but warned of uncertainty stemming from the conflict in the Middle East. </p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  Bank Negara Malaysia expects the Southeast Asian economy to expand between 4% and 5% this year, after a strong finish to 2025 brought annual growth to 5.2% despite headwinds from U.S. trade policy. </p><p>\n\n  It expects solid household spending and investment at home, plus sustained global demand for Malaysia's exports and steady tourism flows, to underpin the economy this year. </p><p>\n\n  \"Our standing as a net energy exporter will also lend us some resilience against the increase in global commodity prices,\" BNM Gov. Abdul Rasheed Ghaffour said in a report on Tuesday. </p><p>\n\n  The conflict involving the U.S. and Israel against Iran has clouded the outlook for Asian economies, which rely heavily on energy from the Middle East. As oil and gas prices surge and supplies are disrupted, concerns about an inflationary shock are growing. </p><p>\n\n  Malaysia is in a better place than most thanks to its energy resources, and the fiscal capacity to blunt the price hit to consumers in the near term, but a sustained conflict will pressure government finances and businesses face a margin squeeze from rising input costs. </p><p>\n\n  Ghaffour said that Malaysia's domestic resilience and diversified exports provide a buffer against external headwinds but warned about far-reaching spillovers on commodity prices and financial markets, saying that the extent of the impact on growth and inflation ultimately hinges on the duration, intensity and severity of the conflict. </p><p>\n\n  \"The developments in the Middle East underscore that conflict can create ripples across the globe, while benefiting none,\" he said. </p><p>\n\n  For now, the central bank expects inflation to stay in check. It forecasts moderate price growth of between 1.5% and 2.5% this year, noting that targeted policies are in place to help cushion the impact on households and businesses. </p><p>\n\n  Still, the cost of those policies might become too high if the fighting drags on. </p><p>\n\n  Malaysia's finance ministry estimates that the country's fuel-subsidy bill could reach 4 billion ringgit, equivalent to $996.6 million, per month, when oil prices hit $100 per barrel. </p><p>\n\n  As costs rise, the government recently announced it will reduce the subsidised fuel quota to 200 liters a month from 300 liters starting in April, while the price of subsidised RON95--the most widely used fuel--will remain capped at 1.99 ringgit, equivalent to about $0.50 per liter. </p><br/><p>\n  Write to Ying Xian Wong at yingxian.wong@wsj.com </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><p>\n\n  03-30-26 2242ET</p></div>",
